Solution 7

library(dplyr)

# Count the number of reviews per country
country_counts <- chocolate %>%
  count(country_of_bean_origin)

# Filter the dataset to include only countries with at least 50 reviews
valid_countries <- country_counts %>%
  filter(n >= 50) %>%
  pull(country_of_bean_origin)

# Filter the original dataset to include only reviews from valid countries
filtered_chocolate <- chocolate %>%
  filter(country_of_bean_origin %in% valid_countries)
# Convert percentage to numeric and create groups
filtered_chocolate <- filtered_chocolate %>%
  mutate(
    cocoa_percent = as.numeric(sub("%", "", cocoa_percent)),  # Remove "%" and convert to numeric
    percentage_group = case_when(
      cocoa_percent < 60 ~ "<60%",
      cocoa_percent >= 60 & cocoa_percent < 70 ~ ">=60 to <70%",
      cocoa_percent >= 70 & cocoa_percent < 90 ~ ">=70 to <90%",
      cocoa_percent >= 90 ~ ">=90%" ) )
library(forcats)

# Re-order the percentage groups
filtered_chocolate <- filtered_chocolate %>%
  mutate(percentage_group = fct_relevel(percentage_group, "<60%", ">=60 to <70%", ">=70 to <90%", ">=90%"))
library(ggplot2)

# Create the boxplots
ggplot(filtered_chocolate, aes(x = percentage_group, y = rating)) +
  geom_boxplot() +
  facet_wrap(~ country_of_bean_origin) +
  labs(x = "Chocolate Percentage Group", y = "Rating") +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, hjust = 1))

# Calculate average rating for each percentage group
average_ratings <- filtered_chocolate %>%
  group_by(percentage_group) %>%
  summarize(mean_rating = mean(rating, na.rm = TRUE))

# Display the result
print(average_ratings)
## # A tibble: 4  2
##   percentage_group mean_rating
##   <fct>                  <dbl>
## 1 <60%                    2.96
## 2 >=60 to <70%            3.25
## 3 >=70 to <90%            3.22
## 4 >=90%                   2.49

part 3

# Load necessary libraries
library(dplyr)
library(tidyr)
library(stringr)

library("here")
chocolate <- readRDS(here("data", "chocolate.RDS"))
# Create ingredient columns
chocolate <- chocolate %>%
  mutate(beans = ifelse(str_detect(ingredients, "beans"), 1, 0),
         sugar = ifelse(str_detect(ingredients, "sugar"), 1, 0),
         cocoa_butter = ifelse(str_detect(ingredients, "cocoa_butter"), 1, 0),
         vanilla = ifelse(str_detect(ingredients, "vanilla"), 1, 0),
         letchin = ifelse(str_detect(ingredients, "letchin"), 1, 0),
         salt = ifelse(str_detect(ingredients, "salt"), 1, 0))

chocolate<- chocolate %>%
  mutate(
    char_cocoa = ifelse(str_detect(most_memorable_characteristics, "cocoa"), 1, 0),
    char_sweet = ifelse(str_detect(most_memorable_characteristics, "sweet"), 1, 0),
    char_nutty = ifelse(str_detect(most_memorable_characteristics, "nutty"), 1, 0),
    char_creamy = ifelse(str_detect(most_memorable_characteristics, "creamy"), 1, 0),
    char_roasty = ifelse(str_detect(most_memorable_characteristics, "roasty"), 1, 0),
    char_earthy = ifelse(str_detect(most_memorable_characteristics, "earthy"), 1, 0)
  )
mean_characteristics_by_year <- chocolate %>%
  group_by(review_date) %>%
  summarise(
    beans = mean(beans, na.rm = TRUE),
    sugar = mean(sugar, na.rm = TRUE),
    cocoa_butter = mean(cocoa_butter, na.rm = TRUE),
    vanilla = mean(vanilla, na.rm = TRUE),
    letchin = mean(letchin, na.rm = TRUE),
    salt = mean(salt, na.rm = TRUE),
    char_cocoa = mean(char_cocoa, na.rm = TRUE),
    char_sweet = mean(char_sweet, na.rm = TRUE),
    char_nutty = mean(char_nutty, na.rm = TRUE),
    char_creamy = mean(char_creamy, na.rm = TRUE),
    char_roasty = mean(char_roasty, na.rm = TRUE),
    char_earthy = mean(char_earthy, na.rm = TRUE)
  )
long_chocolate <- mean_characteristics_by_year %>%
  pivot_longer(cols = -review_date, names_to = "feature", values_to = "mean_score")

# View the result
print(long_chocolate)

Part 6

library(ggplot2)
library(dplyr)

# Sample dataset for illustration
set.seed(123)
chocolate <- data.frame(
  review_date = rep(2000:2005, each = 10),
  rating = runif(60, 0, 10)
)

# Improved plot
ggplot(chocolate, aes(x = as.factor(review_date), y = rating, fill = as.factor(review_date))) +
  geom_violin(alpha = 0.7, color = "black") +  # Semi-transparent fill with border
  geom_jitter(width = 0.2, color = "gray50", size = 2, alpha = 0.5) +  # Add jittered points
  labs(
    title = "Distribution of Ratings Over Time",
    subtitle = "Violin plots showing the spread of ratings for each year",
    x = "Year",
    y = "Rating",
    fill = "Year",
    caption = "Created by Deeksha Tomar"
  ) +
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(
    panel.grid.major = element_line(color = "grey80"),  # Light grid lines for readability
    panel.grid.minor = element_blank(),  # Remove minor grid lines
    axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, hjust = 1),  # Rotate x-axis labels for readability
    plot.title = element_text(size = 16, face = "bold"),
    plot.subtitle = element_text(size = 12),
    plot.caption = element_text(size = 10)
  ) +
  scale_fill_brewer(palette = "Set3")  # Use a color palette for better fill colors

7 points:-

1 I have added black border in the plots, he border color helps define the shape of each distribution clearly.r (geom_violin(alpha = 0.7, color = black))

2 I have done Jittering to spread out points along the x-axis to avoid overplotting, and the semi-transparent gray color ensures the points are visible but not too dominant.the color looks subtle. geom_jitter(width = 0.2, color = gray50, size = 2, alpha = 0.5)

3 Descriptive labels (labs(title, subtitle, x, y, fill, caption)): I have added informative titles, subtitles, and axis labels clarifies the plots purpose and content. This helps viewers understand the context and specifics of the data being presented.

4 Light grid lines (panel.grid.major = element_line(color = grey80)): Added light grid lines to enhance readability of the plot by providing visual reference points without overwhelming the data.

5 Removed minor grid lines (panel.grid.minor = element_blank()): Removing minor grid lines reduces visual clutter, making the plot cleaner and easier to interpret.

6 Rotated x-axis labels (axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, hjust = 1)): Rotated the x-axis labels preventing overlap making them more readable, especially when there are many categories or long labels.

7 Used a color palette (scale_fill_brewer(palette = Set3)): Applying a color palette from the RColorBrewer package ensures that the fill colors are both distinct and aesthetically pleasing. It helps differentiate between categories clearly.
